  <static seed="522" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/IdentifyAxisVertex50.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the axis of symmetry and vertex of the quadratic function.</p>
<p><m>{y}={3x^{2}+6x-1}</m></p>
<p>Axis of symmetry: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p>Vertex: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>x = -1</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(-1,-4\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>This quadratic function is given in standard form. Identify that:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ a=3,b=6,c=-1 }</m></p>
<p>To find the parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry, we use the formula <m>\displaystyle{x=-\frac{b}{2a}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
  x \amp = -\frac{b}{2a} \\
   \amp = -\frac{6}{2(3)} \\
   \amp = -1
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s axis is <m>\displaystyle{x=-1}</m>.</p>
<p>Next, we substitute <m>\displaystyle{x=-1}</m> into <m>\displaystyle{{y}={3x^{2}+6x-1}}</m>:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = 3(-1)^{2}+6(-1) - 1 \\
    \amp = 3 \cdot 1  - 6  - 1 \\
    \amp = {-4}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s vertex is <m>\displaystyle{(-1,{-4})}</m>.</p>
</solution>
